@ossi: by dump I take it that you mean QMAKE_BUNDLE_DATA should only copy files verbatim into the bundle? That is not the case, xib files will be compiled, png's compressed etc (ref also https://codereview.qt-project.org/#/c/97868/). Even adding asset catalogs will result in icons being copied into the bundle with correct naming instead of the catalog itself. Xcode contains a whole set of rules that will apply to files added with QMAKE_BUNDLE_DATA. Files will also be end up at different places depending on which platform you're on. And we don't document this either. Setting up Xcode to use bundled asset catalogs will therefore not change much with regards to making fun of the user.

Also note that when I talk about a cross-platform way of specifying app icons, I'm not referring to qmake. We need a qt_manifest or similar that is not coupled with the build system. We had a meeting about this at contr. summit 2013, where Fawzi agreed to investigate. The point is, this WILL be done. But right now (AFAIK) its up in the air who will do it, and when. But lets be careful dropping small API additions here and there until this is ready.

